[[File:Aegeansea.jpg|alt=|thumb|The [[Aegean Sea]] with its large number of islands is the origin of the term ''archipelago''.]]
[[File:MerguiArchipelagoMap.png|thumb|The [[Mergui Archipelago]] in [[Myanmar]]]]
An '''archipelago''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-us-archipelago.ogg|ˌ|ɑːr|k|ɪ|ˈ|p|ɛ|l|ə|ɡ|oʊ}} {{respell|ARK|ih|PEL|ə|goh}}), sometimes called an '''island group''' or '''island chain''', is a chain, cluster or collection of [[island]]s, or sometimes a sea containing a small number of scattered islands.

[[Indonesia]], the [[Galápagos Islands]], [[Japan]], the [[Philippines]], [[Maldives]], the [[Balearic Isles]], [[the Bahamas]], the [[Aegean Islands]], [[Hawaii]], the [[Canary Islands]], the [[Azores]], and the [[Archipelago Sea]] (Finland) are all examples of well-known archipelagos.

